{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":611,"text":"So, last month, the Encyclopaedia Britannica announced"},{"time":3997,"text":"that it is going out of print"},{"time":5746,"text":"after 244 years, which made me nostalgic,"},{"time":9571,"text":"because I remember playing a game with the colossal encyclopedia set in my hometown library"},{"time":15218,"text":"back when I was a kid,"},{"time":16467,"text":"maybe 12 years old."},{"time":17810,"text":"And I wondered if I could update that game,"},{"time":20450,"text":"not just for modern methods,"},{"time":22466,"text":"but for the modern me."}]},{"cues":[{"time":24170,"text":"So I tried."},{"time":25306,"text":"I went to an online encyclopedia,"},{"time":26613,"text":"Wikipedia, and I entered the term \"Earth.\""},{"time":29371,"text":"You can start anywhere, this time I chose Earth."},{"time":32037,"text":"And the first rule of the game is pretty simple."},{"time":34515,"text":"You just have to read the article"},{"time":36006,"text":"until you find something you don't know,"},{"time":38594,"text":"and preferably something your dad doesn't even know."}]},{"cues":[{"time":41699,"text":"And in this case, I quickly found this:"},{"time":44578,"text":"The furthest point from the center of the Earth"},{"time":46874,"text":"is not the tip of Mount Everest, like I might have thought,"},{"time":49347,"text":"it's the tip of this mountain: Mount Chimborazo in Ecuador."},{"time":52643,"text":"The Earth spins, of course, as it travels around the sun,"},{"time":56163,"text":"so the Earth bulges a little bit around the middle,"},{"time":58147,"text":"like some Earthlings."},{"time":59274,"text":"And even though Mount Chimborazo isn't the tallest mountain in the Andes,"},{"time":64164,"text":"it's one degree away from the equator,"},{"time":65835,"text":"it's riding that bulge, and so the summit of Chimborazo"},{"time":68835,"text":"is the farthest point on Earth from the center of the Earth."}]},{"cues":[{"time":72235,"text":"And it is really fun to say."},{"time":75187,"text":"So I immediately decided,"},{"time":76130,"text":"this is going to be the name of the game,"},{"time":78027,"text":"or my new exclamation."},{"time":79514,"text":"You can use it at TED."},{"time":80484,"text":"Chimborazo, right?"},{"time":81813,"text":"It's like \"eureka\" and \"bingo\" had a baby."},{"time":83515,"text":"I didn't know that;"},{"time":85244,"text":"that's pretty cool."},{"time":86874,"text":"Chimborazo!"}]},{"cues":[{"time":88539,"text":"So the next rule of the game is also pretty simple."},{"time":92164,"text":"You just have to find another term and look that up."},{"time":95051,"text":"Now in the old days, that meant getting out a volume"},{"time":97216,"text":"and browsing through it alphabetically,"},{"time":98851,"text":"maybe getting sidetracked,"},{"time":99890,"text":"that was fun."}]},{"cues":[{"time":100595,"text":"Nowadays there are hundreds of links to choose from."},{"time":103226,"text":"I can go literally anywhere in the world,"},{"time":105178,"text":"I think since I was already in Ecuador,"},{"time":106907,"text":"I just decided to click on the word \"tropical.\""},{"time":109618,"text":"That took me to this wet and warm band of the tropics"},{"time":114859,"text":"that encircles the Earth."}]},{"cues":[{"time":116044,"text":"Now that's the Tropic of Cancer in the north"},{"time":118505,"text":"and the Tropic of Capricorn in the south,"},{"time":120018,"text":"that much I knew,"},{"time":120826,"text":"but I was surprised to learn this little fact:"},{"time":123027,"text":"Those are not cartographers' lines,"},{"time":125293,"text":"like latitude or the borders between nations,"},{"time":128898,"text":"they are astronomical phenomena caused by the Earth's tilt,"},{"time":131629,"text":"and they change."},{"time":133234,"text":"They move; they go up, they go down."},{"time":135884,"text":"In fact, for years, the Tropic of Cancer and the Tropic of Capricorn"},{"time":139083,"text":"have been steadily drifting towards the equator"},{"time":141723,"text":"at the rate of about 15 meters per year,"},{"time":144220,"text":"and nobody told me that."},{"time":145386,"text":"I didn't know it."},{"time":146210,"text":"Chimborazo!"}]},{"cues":[{"time":147628,"text":"So to keep the game going, I just have to find another term and look that one up."},{"time":153404,"text":"Since I'm already in the tropics, I chose \"Tropical rainforest.\""},{"time":157203,"text":"Famous for its diversity, human diversity."},{"time":159486,"text":"There are still dozens and dozens of uncontacted tribes living on this planet."},{"time":165012,"text":"They're all over the globe, but virtually all of them live in tropical rainforests."},{"time":169490,"text":"This is the only place you can go nowadays and not get \"friended.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":174467,"text":"The link that I clicked on here was exotic in the beginning and then absolutely mysterious at the very end."},{"time":183332,"text":"It mentioned leopards and ring-tailed coatis and poison dart frogs and boa constrictors and then"},{"time":190092,"text":"coleoptera,"},{"time":192027,"text":"which turn out to be beetles."}]},{"cues":[{"time":195266,"text":"Now I clicked on this on purpose,"},{"time":197490,"text":"but if I'd somehow gotten here by mistake,"},{"time":199044,"text":"it does remind me, for the band, see \"The Beatles,\""},{"time":201141,"text":"for the car see \"Volkswagon Beetle,\""},{"time":202747,"text":"but I am here for beetle beetles."},{"time":205484,"text":"This is the most successful order on the planet by far."},{"time":209354,"text":"Something between 20 and 25 percent of all life forms on the planet,"},{"time":213604,"text":"including plants, are beetles."},{"time":215410,"text":"That means the next time you are in the grocery store,"},{"time":217593,"text":"take a look at the four people ahead of you in line."},{"time":219795,"text":"Statistically, one of you is a beetle."}]},{"cues":[{"time":222812,"text":"And if it is you, you are astonishingly well adapted."},{"time":228410,"text":"There are scavenger beetles that pick the skin and flesh off of bones in museums."},{"time":233443,"text":"There are predator beetles, that attack other insects"},{"time":236524,"text":"and still look pretty cute to us."},{"time":238307,"text":"There are beetles that roll little balls of dung"},{"time":241811,"text":"great distances across the desert floor to feed to their hatchlings."},{"time":245106,"text":"This reminded the ancient Egyptians of their god Khepri,"},{"time":248890,"text":"who renews the ball of the sun every morning,"},{"time":252204,"text":"which is how that dung-rolling scarab"},{"time":254227,"text":"became that sacred scarab on the breastplate of the Pharaoh Tutankhamun."}]},{"cues":[{"time":259595,"text":"Beetles, I was reminded, have the most romantic flirtation in the animal kingdom."},{"time":265523,"text":"Fireflies are not flies, fireflies are beetles."},{"time":268106,"text":"Fireflies are coleoptera, and coleoptera communicate in other ways as well."}]},{"cues":[{"time":273418,"text":"Like my next link:"},{"time":274794,"text":"The chemical language of pheromones."},{"time":277733,"text":"Now the pheromone page took me to a video of a sea urchin having sex."},{"time":283786,"text":"Yeah."}]},{"cues":[{"time":287466,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":290554,"text":"And the link to aphrodisiac."},{"time":292626,"text":"Now that's something that increases sexual desire,"},{"time":294290,"text":"possibly chocolate."},{"time":296491,"text":"There is a compound in chocolate called phenethylamine"},{"time":299994,"text":"that might be an aphrodisiac."},{"time":301364,"text":"But as the article mentions,"},{"time":303619,"text":"because of enzyme breakdown,"},{"time":304834,"text":"it's unlikely that phenethylamine will reach your brain if taken orally."},{"time":309004,"text":"So those of you who only eat your chocolate, you might have to experiment."}]},{"cues":[{"time":312114,"text":"The link I clicked on here,"},{"time":315924,"text":"\"sympathetic magic,\" mostly because I understand what both of those words mean."},{"time":321123,"text":"But not when they're together like that."},{"time":323275,"text":"I do like sympathy. I do like magic."},{"time":326266,"text":"So when I click on \"sympathetic magic,\""},{"time":327611,"text":"I get sympathetic magic and voodoo dolls."}]},{"cues":[{"time":332416,"text":"This is the boy in me getting lucky again."},{"time":334564,"text":"Sympathetic magic is imitation."},{"time":337083,"text":"If you imitate something, maybe you can have an effect on it."},{"time":339490,"text":"That's the idea behind voodoo dolls, and possibly also cave paintings."}]},{"cues":[{"time":343924,"text":"The link to cave paintings takes me to some of the oldest art known to humankind."},{"time":349004,"text":"I would love to see Google maps inside some of these caves."},{"time":351011,"text":"We've got tens-of-thousands-years-old artwork."},{"time":354507,"text":"Common themes around the globe include large wild animals and tracings of human hands,"},{"time":359506,"text":"usually the left hand."}]},{"cues":[{"time":361827,"text":"We have been a dominantly right-handed tribe for millenia,"},{"time":366290,"text":"so even though I don't know why a paleolithic person would trace his hand"},{"time":371626,"text":"or blow pigment on it from a tube,"},{"time":373612,"text":"I can easily picture how he did it."},{"time":376204,"text":"And I really don't think it's that different form our own little dominant hand avatar"},{"time":380706,"text":"right there that I'm going to use now to click on the term for \"hand,\""},{"time":384038,"text":"go to the page for \"hand,\" where I found the most fun and possibly embarrassing bit of trivia"},{"time":390330,"text":"I've found in a long time. It's simply this:"},{"time":392364,"text":"The back of the hand is formally called the opisthenar."}]},{"cues":[{"time":396546,"text":"Now that's embarrassing, because up until now,"},{"time":400219,"text":"every time I've said, \"I know it like the back of my hand,\""},{"time":403419,"text":"I've really been saying, \"I'm totally familiar with that,"},{"time":405778,"text":"I just don't know it's freaking name, right?\""},{"time":408364,"text":"And the link I clicked on here,"},{"time":412018,"text":"well, lemurs, monkeys and chimpanzees have the little opisthenar."}]},{"cues":[{"time":416170,"text":"I click on chimpanzee, and I get our closest genetic relative."},{"time":420420,"text":"Pan troglodytes, the name we give him, means \"cave dweller.\""},{"time":424411,"text":"He doesn't."},{"time":425915,"text":"He lives in rainforests and savannas."},{"time":427739,"text":"It's just that we're always thinking of this guy as lagging behind us,"},{"time":430946,"text":"evolutionarily or somehow uncannily creeping up on us,"},{"time":434010,"text":"and in some cases, he gets places before us."}]},{"cues":[{"time":437684,"text":"Like my next link, the almost irresistible link, Ham the Astrochimp."},{"time":442906,"text":"I click on him, and I really thought he was going to bring me full circle twice, in fact."},{"time":447084,"text":"He's born in Cameroon,"},{"time":448284,"text":"which is smack in the middle of my tropics map,"},{"time":452044,"text":"and more specifically his skeleton wound up in the Smithsonian museum getting picked clean by beetles."}]},{"cues":[{"time":458266,"text":"In between those two landmarks in Ham's life,"},{"time":461219,"text":"he flew into space."},{"time":463755,"text":"He experienced weightlessness and re-entry"},{"time":466992,"text":"months before the first human being to do it,"},{"time":469563,"text":"Soviet cosmonaut Yuri Gagarin."}]},{"cues":[{"time":472427,"text":"When I click on Yuri Gagarin's page,"},{"time":474579,"text":"I get this guy who was surprisingly short in stature,"},{"time":477498,"text":"huge in heroism."},{"time":479035,"text":"Top estimates, Soviet estimates, put this guy at 1.65 meters,"},{"time":483378,"text":"that is less than five and a half feet tall max,"},{"time":486379,"text":"possibly because he was malnourished as a child."}]},{"cues":[{"time":489185,"text":"Germans occupied Russia."},{"time":491730,"text":"A Nazi officer took over the Gagarin household,"},{"time":494827,"text":"and he and his family built and lived in a mud hut."},{"time":497631,"text":"Years later, the boy from that cramped mud hut"},{"time":501178,"text":"would grow up to be the man in that cramped capsule"},{"time":504684,"text":"on the tip of a rocket"},{"time":506298,"text":"who volunteered to be launched into outer space,"},{"time":509786,"text":"the first one of any of us to really physically leave this planet."},{"time":514138,"text":"And he didn't just leave it,"},{"time":515486,"text":"he circled it once."}]},{"cues":[{"time":518011,"text":"Fifty years later, as a tribute,"},{"time":520237,"text":"the International Space Station, which is still up there tonight,"},{"time":524164,"text":"synced its orbit with Gagarin's orbit,"},{"time":528244,"text":"at the exact same time of day,"},{"time":529410,"text":"and filmed it,"},{"time":530970,"text":"so you can go online and you can watch over 100 minutes"},{"time":534554,"text":"of what must have been an absolutely mesmerizing ride,"},{"time":538063,"text":"possibly a lonely one,"},{"time":539204,"text":"the first person to ever see such a thing."}]},{"cues":[{"time":541484,"text":"And then when you've had your fill of that,"},{"time":542907,"text":"you can click on one more link."},{"time":545524,"text":"You can come back to Earth."},{"time":546866,"text":"You return to where you started."},{"time":549027,"text":"You can finish your game."},{"time":551244,"text":"You just need to find one more fact that you didn't know."}]},{"cues":[{"time":554834,"text":"And for me, I quickly landed on this one:"},{"time":557314,"text":"The Earth has a tolerance of about .17 percent from the reference spheroid,"},{"time":562330,"text":"which is less than the .22 percent allowed in billiard balls."}]},{"cues":[{"time":566299,"text":"This is the kind of fact I would have loved as a boy."},{"time":568731,"text":"I found it myself."},{"time":569978,"text":"It's got some math that I can do."},{"time":572253,"text":"I'm pretty sure my dad doesn't know it."},{"time":574378,"text":"What this means is that if you could shrink the Earth to the size of a billiard ball,"},{"time":579867,"text":"if you could take planet Earth, with all its mountain tops and caves"},{"time":585884,"text":"and rainforests, astronauts and uncontacted tribes and chimpanzees, voodoo dolls,"},{"time":590560,"text":"fireflies, chocolate, sea creatures making love in the deep blue sea,"},{"time":596084,"text":"you just shrink that to the size of a billiard ball,"},{"time":599285,"text":"it would be as smooth as a billiard ball,"},{"time":603178,"text":"presumably a billiard ball with a slight bulge around the middle."}]},{"cues":[{"time":607795,"text":"That's pretty cool."},{"time":610586,"text":"I didn't know that."},{"time":612530,"text":"Chimborazo!"}]},{"cues":[{"time":614755,"text":"Thank you."}]},{"cues":[{"time":615644,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}